# Structural Bioinformatics — Mutant Construct Analysis


## Overview

Computational and experimental analysis of protein mutant constructs,
combining multiple sequence alignment, homology modeling, and structural
validation with wet-lab site-directed mutagenesis and protein characterisation.

---

## Methods

### Computational

| Method | Tool | Purpose |
|--------|------|---------|
| Multiple sequence alignment | ClustalW · BLAST | Conserved region identification |
| Homology modeling | Swiss-Model · Modeller | 3D structure prediction from sequence |
| Structural validation | PyMOL · PROCHECK | Ramachandran plot, geometry checks |
| Conformational analysis | PyMOL | Mutation site visualisation |

### Experimental

- Site-directed mutagenesis — introducing specific point mutations
- Primer design — mutation-specific primers for PCR
- Cloning — insertion of mutant constructs into expression vectors
- Sequence validation — confirming mutations by Sanger sequencing
- Protein expression and characterisation

---

## Workflow

```
Target protein sequence
        │
        ▼
BLAST homology search → template selection
        │
        ▼
Multiple sequence alignment (ClustalW)
        │
        ▼
Homology model generation (Swiss-Model)
        │
        ▼
Structural validation (PyMOL · PROCHECK)
        │
        ▼
Mutation site analysis → primer design
        │
        ▼
Site-directed mutagenesis (wet lab)
        │
        ▼
Sequence confirmation → protein expression
```

---

## Key tools

```bash
# BLAST sequence search
blastp -query protein.fasta -db nr -out blast_results.txt -evalue 0.001

# ClustalW alignment
clustalw2 -INFILE=sequences.fasta -OUTFILE=aligned.aln -TYPE=PROTEIN

# PyMOL structural analysis
# Load structure, visualise mutation sites, measure distances
pymol structure.pdb
```

